      "widgets_values": [
        "MANUAL VISUAL TEST — does 📽 Project still work correctly under a\nShotCam that's deliberately a very different aspect ratio from the\nsource photo?\n\nSetup: AtlasDefineShotCam here is set to 36x15.06mm (2.39:1\nanamorphic widescreen) at 2048px long edge — almost certainly very\ndifferent from whatever aspect ratio your source photo actually is.\nIt's wired DIRECTLY into AtlasBlockoutViewport's shot_cam input.\n\nSTEPS:\n1. Queue this workflow, then open the AtlasBlockoutViewport node.\n2. Confirm the canvas is now letterboxed to 2.39:1 — noticeably\n   wider/shorter than the source photo's own aspect.\n3. Click 📽 Project. From the initial (recovered) camera view, the\n   photo should still project back onto the geometry perfectly\n   sharp and undistorted — because the ShotCam only ever changes the\n   RENDER camera's format, never the texture-sampling math used to\n   paint the photo onto geometry (see CLAUDE.md's \"ShotCam\" entry\n   for why that separation holds).\n4. Orbit slightly and confirm the projected texture still tracks\n   correctly with parallax, exactly like it would with no ShotCam\n   connected at all.\n5. Toggle ℹ Info — the HUD's focal/sensor/FOV readout should still\n   describe the ORIGINAL solved camera (e.g. ~35-70mm depending on\n   the photo), NOT the ShotCam's 35mm/2.39:1 — those are diagnostics\n   about how the photo was actually shot, deliberately untouched.\n\nIf 📽 Project shows any misalignment, warping, or the wrong crop of\nthe source photo once a ShotCam is connected, that's a regression —\nexpected result is: identical projection accuracy to no-ShotCam,\njust a different render canvas shape around it.\n\nTry disconnecting shot_cam afterwards and re-queuing to compare\ndirectly against the original source-aspect-following behavior."
      ]
    }
